### Medieval Historiography

#### Bede and Alfred the Great

[Bede](/Bede), whose life concluded in 735, provided a pivotal account. He stated that the Anglii, before their migration to Britain, inhabited a land called Angulus, situated "between the province of the Jutes and the Saxons, and remains unpopulated to this day." This description, possibly echoed in the 9th-century *[Historia Brittonum](/Historia_Brittonum)*, was later identified by King [Alfred the Great](/Alfred_the_Great) and the chronicler [Æthelweard](/%C3%86thelweard_(historian)) with the region of Angeln in the province of [Schleswig](/Schleswig), though its extent might have been greater in Bede's time. This identification aligns with Bede's own indications.

The Norwegian seafarer [Ohthere of Hålogaland](/Ohthere_of_H%C3%A5logaland), in his account of a voyage from the [Oslo fjord](/Oslofjord) to [Schleswig](/Duchy_of_Schleswig), reported seeing lands on his starboard bow. Alfred appended a note to this, stating, "on these islands dwelt the Engle before they came hither." This corroborates the geographical connection.

Further evidence emerges from English and Danish traditions. These traditions speak of two kings, [Wermund](/Wermund) and [Offa of Angel](/Offa_of_Angel), from whom the royal family of [Mercia](/Mercia) claimed descent. Their exploits are intricately linked to Angeln, Schleswig, and [Rendsburg](/Rendsburg).

Danish tradition also preserves the memory of two governors of Schleswig, father and son: Frowinus ([Freawine](/Freawine)) and [Wigo](/Ket_and_Wig). The royal family of [Wessex](/Wessex) claimed descent from these figures. It was during the fifth century that the Anglii began their invasion of Great Britain. After this period, their name on the continent largely disappears, except for its inclusion in the title of a legal code issued to the [Thuringians](/Thuringii): the *[Lex Angliorum et Werinorum hoc est Thuringorum](/Lex_Angliorum_et_Werinorum_hoc_est_Thuringorum)*.

#### The Legend of Pope Gregory I

A famous legend, recounted by Bede, concerns [Pope Gregory I](/Pope_Gregory_I). The story goes that Gregory, while passing through the Roman slave market, encountered a group of fair-haired children from [Deira](/Deira) being offered for sale. Struck by their striking appearance, he inquired about their origin. Upon learning they were called "Anglii" (Angles), he uttered a memorable Latin pun: "Bene, nam et angelicam habent faciem, et tales angelorum in caelis decet esse coheredes" – "It is well, for they have an angelic face, and such people ought to be co-heirs of the angels in heaven." This encounter is said to have ignited his desire to bring Christianity to their homeland. It's a story that humanizes the vast, impersonal sweep of migration and conquest, giving it a divine impetus.

